  "summary": "After a conversation with Colonel Baker, who warns him against succumbing to the chaos of the world, Colin Lamb reads a newspaper report stating that Madame Melina Rival has died in the hospital. She had collapsed at Victoria Station due to exhaustion after being discovered to have been stabbed.\n\nColin calls Inspector Hakastad, who reveals that he had previously visited Madame Rival. Hakastad shares his theory that Madame Rival had been paid to falsely identify a corpse as her long-abandoned husband, Harry Castleton, in order to protect certain business interests. Hakastad notes that following Colin's recent visit, Madame Rival made a phone call and then traveled to Crofton during rush hour, where she was likely stabbed by a killer hiding in the crowd. Colin informs Hakastad of a witness report regarding a large laundry basket delivered to 19 Wilbraham Crescent by a man in a car from Snowflake Laundry on September 9th.\n\nFive days later, Colin arrives in Crofton and stays at the Clarendon Hotel. Upon waking, he receives a thick, expensive envelope containing a note that reads: \"Curlew Hotel, 11:30, Room 413 (Knock three times!)\" Noting that the room number matches the time, Colin proceeds to the Mallard Inn. He goes to Room 413 and knocks three times as instructed. Upon entering the unlocked room, he finds Hercule Poirot, who surprises him by revealing he arrived in a luxury Mercedes-Benz.",
